% Calculate the magnitude (length) of the vector
magnitude = norm(vector);

% Normalize the vector
normalized_vector = vector ./ magnitude;

disp(normalized_vector);
```

### In C++ (Using Eigen Library)

The Eigen library is a popular choice for linear algebra operations in C++.

```cpp
#include <Eigen/Dense>
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    // Define a vector
    Eigen::Vector2d vector(3, 4);

    // Calculate the magnitude (length) of the vector
    double magnitude = vector.norm();

    // Normalize the vector
    Eigen::Vector2d normalized_vector = vector / magnitude;

    std::cout << normalized_vector << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

### In Java (Using Apache Commons Math)

Apache Commons Math is a library that provides mathematical and statistical components.

```java
import org.apache.commons.math3.linear.Array2DRowRealMatrix;
import org.apache.commons.math3.linear.RealMatrix;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Define a vector
        double[][] vector = {{3, 4}};

        // Create a RealMatrix from the vector
        RealMatrix matrix = new Array2DRowRealMatrix(vector);

        // Calculate the magnitude (length) of the vector
        double magnitude = matrix.getNorm(1);

        // Normalize the vector
        RealMatrix normalizedMatrix = matrix.map(new Normalize(magnitude));

        // Print the normalized vector
        System.out.println(normalizedMatrix);
    }
}

class Normalize implements RealMatrixFunction {
    private final double magnitude;

    public Normalize(double magnitude) {
        this.magnitude = magnitude;
    }

    @Override
    public double evaluate(double[] in) {
        return in[0] / magnitude;
    }
}
```

Each of these examples demonstrates how to normalize a vector in a different programming context. The process involves calculating the magnitude of the vector and then dividing the vector by its magnitude to produce a unit vector.

