To draw a chessboard in LaTeX, representing a specific state as given by a FEN (Forsyth-Edwards Notation) string, you can use the `skak` package, which is specifically designed for typesetting chess boards and games in LaTeX. However, for a more straightforward approach without relying on the `skak` package, you can use the `tikz` package, which is a powerful tool for creating graphics in LaTeX.

Below is a basic example of how you can draw a chessboard and place pieces on it using the `tikz` package. This example does not directly use FEN notation but shows how to place pieces on a board. To adapt this to a FEN notation, you would need to parse the FEN string and place the pieces accordingly.

First, you need to include the necessary packages in your LaTeX document:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric}

\newcommand{\square}[1]{%
  \node[draw, minimum size=1cm, rectangle, inner sep=0pt] at (#1) {};
}

\newcommand{\piece}[3]{%
  \node at (#1) [circle, draw, minimum size=0.8cm, inner sep=0pt, fill=white, label={#2}] {};
  \node at (#1) [anchor=south, inner sep=0pt] {#3};
}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
  \foreach \i in {0,1,...,7} {
    \foreach \j in {0,1,...,7} {
      \ifodd(\i+\j)
        \fill (\j,\i) rectangle ++(1,1);
      \fi
    }
  }

  \foreach \i in {0,1,...,7} {
    \foreach \j in {0,1,...,7} {
      \ifodd(\i+\j)
        \square{(\j,\i)};
      \else
        \square{(\j,\i)};
      \fi
    }
  }

  % Place pieces
  \piece{(0,0)}{white}{R}
  \piece{(0,1)}{white}{N}
